{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476501"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13769"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13769"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.3,0.09,0.03,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2365"},{"type":"tags","id":"2379"},{"type":"tags","id":"2380"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44173"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department by his parent. Approximately 30 minutes ago, the child accidentally consumed an unknown amount of antifreeze solution that had been incorrectly stored in an unlabelled soft drink container. The boy has no significant medical history and is not on any regular medications. On examination, he appears lethargic but responsive. His vital signs are: pulse rate 130/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Blood tests, including an arterial blood gas, reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.25 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 32 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2 95 mmHg (75-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 12 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate 2.0 mmol/L (0.5-1.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 140 mmol/L (137 \u2013 145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.5 mmol/L (3.5 \u2013 4.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 102 mmol/L (100 \u2013 109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 5.0 mmol/L (3.2 \u2013 5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum osmolality (measured) 340 mOsm/kg (265 \u2013 285)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum osmolality (calculated) 290 mOsm/kg (265 \u2013 285)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium bicarbonate infusion","Fomepizole","Haemodialysis","N-acetylcysteine","Activated charcoal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a child who has ingested ethylene glycol, a toxic alcohol commonly found in antifreeze solutions. While ethylene glycol itself is not highly toxic, its metabolites, produced by alcohol dehydrogenase, are responsible for the harmful effects. These metabolites, including glycolic and oxalic acids, lead to a high anion gap metabolic acidosis, as evidenced by the arterial blood gas results. Additionally, the presence of an osmolar gap (difference between measured and calculated osmolality) further supports the diagnosis of toxic alcohol ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate immediate intervention is administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Efomepizole\u003C/strong\u003E. This antidote works by inhibiting alcohol dehydrogenase, thereby preventing the formation of toxic metabolites from ethylene glycol. By halting this process, fomepizole effectively mitigates the progression of toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E infusion can help manage the metabolic acidosis resulting from ethylene glycol poisoning, it does not address the underlying cause. The priority in this scenario is to prevent further production of toxic metabolites, which is best achieved with fomepizole. Bicarbonate therapy may be considered as an adjunct treatment if the acidosis is severe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential treatment in severe cases of ethylene glycol poisoning. It can effectively remove both the parent compound and its toxic metabolites, as well as correct severe acidosis and manage acute kidney injury. However, dialysis is typically reserved for cases with persistent high ethylene glycol levels despite fomepizole treatment, severe metabolic acidosis (pH \u0026lt; 7.25-7.30), or significant organ dysfunction. Based on the current clinical picture, this child does not meet the criteria for immediate dialysis, although it may be considered if his condition deteriorates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E is the antidote used in paracetamol (acetaminophen) poisoning. It has no role in the management of ethylene glycol toxicity and would not be beneficial in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is ineffective in ethylene glycol poisoning as it does not adsorb alcohols. The focus should be on preventing the metabolism of the already absorbed ethylene glycol.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fomepizole is the primary antidote for ethylene glycol poisoning, acting by inhibiting alcohol dehydrogenase.","Ethylene glycol poisoning leads to the production of toxic metabolites, resulting in a high anion gap metabolic acidosis.","An elevated osmolar gap between measured and calculated serum osmolality is characteristic of ethylene glycol poisoning."],"references":["Marco L A Sivilotti, Methanol and ethylene glycol poisoning: Management, In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/methanol-and-ethylene-glycol-poisoning-management","Brent J, McMartin K, Phillips S, Burkhart KK, Donovan JW, Wells M, Kulig K. Fomepizole for the treatment of ethylene glycol poisoning. Methylpyrazole for Toxic Alcohols Study Group. N Engl J Med. 1999 Mar 18;340(11):832-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10080845/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13769"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T11:33:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T11:34:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","i